{"id":"project-LICHEN-ke3v","title":"loadng.c: prune_countdown can go negative, causing missed prunes","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/routing/loadng.c
Lines: 39, 396-399

The prune countdown logic:

    #define PRUNE_INTERVAL 16
    static int prune_countdown = PRUNE_INTERVAL;

    ...
    prune_countdown--;
    if (prune_countdown <= 0) {
        prune_seen_locked(now_ms);
        prune_countdown = PRUNE_INTERVAL;
    }

If prune_countdown is accessed concurrently (multiple threads calling lichen_loadng_seen_check_and_mark), multiple threads could decrement it simultaneously. The check 'prune_countdown <= 0' handles negative values, but the decrement itself is not atomic.

While the seen_mutex protects the table operations, the countdown is a static global that could experience race conditions between the decrement and the check, potentially causing:
1. Multiple prunes in quick succession
2. Countdown going very negative before reset

Consider making prune_countdown thread-safe or moving it under the mutex.","status":"open","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"me@mark.atwood.name","created_at":"2026-07-12T06:50:10.107606Z","created_by":"Mark Atwood","updated_at":"2026-07-12T06:50:10.107636Z"}
